<h1>TheMakerVoid ELS&nbsp;v1.0</h1>
<p style="font-size:13pt; color:#556483; margin-top:-6px;"><b>Electronic Lead Screw for Metal Lathes — User Manual</b></p>
<p class="small">ESP32-S3 &bull; ILI9341 320&times;240 Touchscreen &bull; Lichuan A6 Servo &bull; 1440&nbsp;p/rev Spindle Encoder</p>

<hr>

<h2>1. Introduction</h2>
<p>The <b>TheMakerVoid ELS</b> (Electronic Lead Screw) is a controller that electronically couples your lathe's spindle to the carriage drive motor. Instead of swapping physical change gears, the controller reads the spindle rotation through a rotary encoder and commands a servo (or stepper) motor to move the carriage at a precisely synchronized ratio. This lets you perform <b>automatic feeding</b> and <b>thread cutting</b> — in both metric and imperial — and use the spindle as an <b>indexing / dividing head</b>, all selected from a touchscreen menu.</p>

<p>The unit is operated either by the <b>resistive touchscreen</b> or by <b>four physical buttons</b> (UP, DOWN, SELECT, BACK). Both input methods are always active and do exactly the same things.</p>

<div class="note"><b>Who this is for:</b> machinists and hobbyists fitting an ELS to a manual lathe. Basic familiarity with lathe feed rates, thread pitch, and TPI is assumed.</div>

<h3>Contents</h3>
<p class="toc">
2. Safety &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 3. Hardware Overview &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 4. Controls &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 5. Powering On &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp;
6. Main Menu &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 7. Feed Mode &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 8. Thread Mode &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 9. Divider Mode &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp;
10. Settings Menu &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 11. Configuration &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 12. Interface &amp; Info &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp;
13. Reference Tables &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 14. Troubleshooting
</p>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>2. Safety</h2>
<div class="warn">
<b>Read before use.</b> An ELS commands carriage motion automatically whenever the spindle turns in Feed or Thread mode. Carelessness can crash the carriage into the chuck or your hands.
</div>
<ul>
  <li>Always know which <b>direction</b> the carriage will travel before engaging. Verify the CW/CCW direction setting (Section&nbsp;11.1) for your machine.</li>
  <li>Keep the <b>BACK</b> control within reach. Pressing BACK from Feed or Thread mode immediately stops the motor and returns to the Main Menu.</li>
  <li>Confirm the configured <b>lead screw pitch</b> (Section&nbsp;11.2) matches your lathe's actual lead screw. A wrong value produces a wrong feed/thread ratio.</li>
  <li>Make a trial pass clear of the workpiece the first time you use a new feed rate or thread pitch.</li>
  <li>The motor only moves while the spindle moves. Stopping the spindle stops the carriage.</li>
</ul>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>3. Hardware Overview</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Component</th><th>Specification</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Microcontroller</td><td>ESP32-S3 DevKit C-1 (dual-core)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Display</td><td>ILI9341 TFT, 320&times;240 px, landscape, resistive touch (XPT2046)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Spindle encoder</td><td>Quadrature rotary encoder, 1440 pulses per revolution</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Motor driver</td><td>Lichuan A6 servo drive, PUL/DIR (step &amp; direction) interface</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Physical input</td><td>4 buttons: UP, DOWN, SELECT, BACK</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Persistent memory</td><td>EEPROM — stores direction, lead screw pitch, and dark mode</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Internally the controller uses both ESP32 cores: one core drives the user interface and screen, while a second dedicated high-priority core does nothing but read the encoder and generate motor pulses in real time. This separation keeps motion accurate and jitter-free even while you navigate menus.</p>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>4. Controls</h2>

<h3>4.1 Physical Buttons</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Button</th><th>General function</th></tr>
  <tr><td><span class="key">UP</span></td><td>Move selection up / previous item / increment a digit</td></tr>
  <tr><td><span class="key">DOWN</span></td><td>Move selection down / next item / decrement a digit</td></tr>
  <tr><td><span class="key">SELECT</span></td><td>Confirm / enter the highlighted option / advance</td></tr>
  <tr><td><span class="key">BACK</span></td><td>Go back one level. From the Main Menu it opens the Settings overlay; from Feed/Thread mode it stops the motor and returns to the Main Menu.</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>4.2 Touchscreen</h3>
<p>Every on-screen button, list item, and arrow can be tapped directly. The screen recognizes one touch at a time and ignores repeats for a fraction of a second to prevent accidental double-taps. Common on-screen icons:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Icon</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
  <tr><td><b>Menu</b> (top-right)</td><td>Opens the Settings overlay (Configuration / Interface / Info).</td></tr>
  <tr><td><b>Back</b> (bottom-right)</td><td>Returns to the previous screen / cancels.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><b>OK</b> (bottom-right, left of Back)</td><td>Confirms the current selection or saves the setting.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><b>Reload</b> (Divider screen)</td><td>Resets the angle reading to zero.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><b>&#9664; / &#9654; carets</b></td><td>Previous / next page in long lists (thread selection).</td></tr>
  <tr><td><b>Stepper &#9650;/&#9660;</b></td><td>Increment / decrement the selected digit (lead screw pitch).</td></tr>
</table>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>5. Powering On</h2>
<p>When power is applied, the controller shows a <b>splash screen</b> with the TheMakerVoid logo for about 5 seconds. You can skip it immediately by touching the screen or pressing any button. After the splash, the <b>Main Menu</b> appears.</p>
<p>On first power-up the controller initializes its saved settings to safe defaults (direction&nbsp;=&nbsp;CW, lead screw pitch&nbsp;=&nbsp;3&nbsp;mm, dark mode&nbsp;=&nbsp;on). On every subsequent boot it restores whatever you last saved.</p>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>6. Main Menu</h2>
<p>The Main Menu is the home screen. It shows the three operating modes on the right and the <b>live spindle RPM</b> at the bottom-left, which updates continuously as the spindle turns (so you can use it as a tachometer at any time).</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Option</th><th>Goes to</th></tr>
  <tr><td><b>FEED</b></td><td>Feed-rate selection &rarr; automatic feeding (Section&nbsp;7)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><b>THREAD</b></td><td>Metric/Imperial choice &rarr; pitch selection &rarr; thread cutting (Section&nbsp;8)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><b>DIVIDER</b></td><td>Live spindle angle / indexing readout (Section&nbsp;9)</td></tr>
</table>
<p><b>Navigation:</b> use <span class="key">UP</span>/<span class="key">DOWN</span> to highlight a mode and <span class="key">SELECT</span> to enter it, or simply tap it. Press <span class="key">BACK</span> (or tap the Menu icon) to open the Settings overlay.</p>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>7. Feed Mode (Automatic Feeding)</h2>
<p>Feed Mode drives the carriage at a fixed distance per spindle revolution — the electronic equivalent of engaging the feed via change gears.</p>

<h3>7.1 Selecting a feed rate</h3>
<p>From the Main Menu choose <b>FEED</b>. A grid of available feed rates (in mm per revolution) appears. The five rates are:</p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><b>0.07 &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 0.10 &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 0.13 &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 0.18 &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 0.25 &nbsp;mm/rev</b></p>
<p>Highlight a rate with <span class="key">UP</span>/<span class="key">DOWN</span> (or tap it), then press <span class="key">SELECT</span> / tap <b>OK</b> to engage.</p>

<h3>7.2 While feeding</h3>
<p>The Feed Mode screen shows the active feed value and the <b>live RPM</b>. As soon as the spindle turns, the controller moves the carriage at the selected rate. Stopping the spindle stops the carriage.</p>
<p>To stop feeding, press <span class="key">BACK</span> or tap <b>Back</b>. This <b>immediately disables the motor</b> and returns you to the Main Menu.</p>

<div class="note">Feed direction follows the configured motor direction (Section&nbsp;11.1) combined with the spindle's rotation direction.</div>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>8. Thread Mode (Thread Cutting)</h2>
<p>Thread Mode synchronizes the carriage to cut a thread of a chosen pitch. It supports both metric pitches and imperial (UTS) threads specified in TPI.</p>

<h3>8.1 Choosing the thread standard</h3>
<p>From the Main Menu choose <b>THREAD</b>. The <b>Thread Unit Switch</b> screen asks which standard you want:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Option</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
  <tr><td><b>METRIC</b></td><td>Pitch specified in millimetres (mm).</td></tr>
  <tr><td><b>UTS</b></td><td>Imperial / Unified threads specified in threads&nbsp;per&nbsp;inch (TPI).</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Toggle with <span class="key">UP</span>/<span class="key">DOWN</span> (or tap), then confirm with <span class="key">SELECT</span> / <b>OK</b>.</p>

<h3>8.2 Selecting the pitch</h3>
<p>A paginated grid of pitches appears (six per page). Use the <b>&#9664;/&#9654; carets</b> at the bottom-left — or keep pressing <span class="key">UP</span>/<span class="key">DOWN</span>, which scrolls across pages automatically and wraps around — to find your pitch. The header shows the units in use, <code>(mm)</code> or <code>(tpi)</code>.</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>Metric:</b> 16 pitches from 0.20&nbsp;mm to 4.00&nbsp;mm.</li>
  <li><b>Imperial (UTS):</b> 21 values from 8&nbsp;TPI to 56&nbsp;TPI.</li>
</ul>
<p>(Full lists in Section&nbsp;13.) Highlight the pitch and press <span class="key">SELECT</span> / tap <b>OK</b> to engage.</p>

<h3>8.3 While cutting</h3>
<p>The Thread Mode screen shows the active pitch (in mm) or TPI value plus the live RPM, and the carriage tracks the spindle at the exact ratio for that thread. As with feeding, press <span class="key">BACK</span> / tap <b>Back</b> to stop the motor and return to the Main Menu.</p>

<div class="warn"><b>Important:</b> the controller maintains the correct lead ratio, but thread cutting still requires correct technique — appropriate spindle speed, retracting the tool at the end of each pass, and re-engaging at the same point. The ELS keeps carriage motion locked to the spindle; it does not automate tool infeed or thread-stop.</div>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>9. Divider Mode (Indexing)</h2>
<p>Divider Mode turns the spindle encoder into a precise <b>angular position readout</b>, useful for indexing work such as bolt-hole circles, flats, gears, or graduations.</p>
<ul>
  <li>The screen shows the current spindle angle in <b>degrees (0&ndash;360&deg;)</b>, updated in real time as you rotate the spindle by hand.</li>
  <li>Tap the <b>Reload</b> icon (or press <span class="key">SELECT</span>) to <b>zero the angle</b> at the current position — set your reference, then rotate to the angle you need.</li>
  <li>Press <span class="key">BACK</span> / tap <b>Back</b> to return to the Main Menu.</li>
</ul>
<p>Because the encoder has 1440 pulses per revolution, the readout resolves to a quarter of a degree.</p>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>10. Settings Menu (Overlay)</h2>
<p>From the Main Menu, press <span class="key">BACK</span> or tap the <b>Menu</b> icon (top-right of most screens) to open the Settings overlay. It offers three items:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Item</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
  <tr><td><b>CONFIGURATION</b></td><td>Set motor direction and lead screw pitch (Section&nbsp;11).</td></tr>
  <tr><td><b>INTERFACE</b></td><td>Toggle dark mode (Section&nbsp;12.1).</td></tr>
  <tr><td><b>INFO</b></td><td>Firmware version and credits (Section&nbsp;12.2).</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Navigate with <span class="key">UP</span>/<span class="key">DOWN</span> + <span class="key">SELECT</span>, or tap. <span class="key">BACK</span> / <b>Back</b> returns to where you came from.</p>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>11. Configuration</h2>
<p>These two settings define how the controller calculates every feed and thread ratio. They are stored permanently in EEPROM and survive power cycles. Set them up once for your machine.</p>

<h3>11.1 Direction (CW / CCW)</h3>
<p>Selects the motor rotation direction that corresponds to forward carriage travel on your lathe.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Tap <b>CW</b> or <b>CCW</b> (or toggle with <span class="key">UP</span>/<span class="key">DOWN</span>).</li>
  <li>Confirm with <b>OK</b> / <span class="key">SELECT</span> to <b>save</b>; the value is written to memory and applied to the motor immediately.</li>
  <li><b>Back</b> cancels without saving.</li>
</ul>
<div class="note">If the carriage runs the wrong way when you engage Feed or Thread mode, return here and switch this setting.</div>

<h3>11.2 Lead Screw Pitch</h3>
<p>Tells the controller the pitch of your lathe's lead screw, in millimetres. This is the reference the ratio math is built on, so it must match your actual machine.</p>
<ul>
  <li>The value is entered as <b>two digits</b> (tens and units), range <b>1&ndash;10&nbsp;mm</b>.</li>
  <li>Tap a digit box to select it, then use the on-screen <b>&#9650;/&#9660; stepper</b> arrows — or <span class="key">UP</span>/<span class="key">DOWN</span> — to change that digit (digits wrap 0&hellip;9).</li>
  <li>Press <b>OK</b> / <span class="key">SELECT</span> to advance from the tens digit to the units digit; pressing it again on the units digit <b>saves</b> the value and returns to the Configuration menu.</li>
  <li><b>Back</b> cancels.</li>
</ul>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>12. Interface &amp; Info</h2>

<h3>12.1 Interface — Dark Mode</h3>
<p>The Interface screen has a single <b>DARK MODE</b> toggle. Tap the slider (or press <span class="key">SELECT</span>) to switch between the dark theme and an inverted (light) theme; the change is shown instantly. The setting is saved when you leave the screen with <b>Back</b>.</p>

<h3>12.2 Info</h3>
<p>The Info screen lists firmware and hardware identification and project credits:</p>
<ul>
  <li>TheMakerVoid ELS v1.0</li>
  <li>ESP32-S3 DevKit C-1 &bull; ILI9341 TFT 320&times;240</li>
  <li>Lichuan A6 Servo &bull; Encoder 1440 p/rev</li>
  <li>An open-source / public-domain project — free to use as you wish.</li>
  <li>Project &amp; donation links to <b>www.themakervoid.com</b>.</li>
</ul>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>13. Reference Tables</h2>

<h3>13.1 Feed rates (mm / revolution)</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>#</th><th>1</th><th>2</th><th>3</th><th>4</th><th>5</th></tr>
  <tr><td><b>mm/rev</b></td><td>0.07</td><td>0.10</td><td>0.13</td><td>0.18</td><td>0.25</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>13.2 Metric thread pitches (mm) — 16 values</h3>
<table>
  <tr><td>0.20</td><td>0.30</td><td>0.40</td><td>0.50</td><td>0.60</td><td>0.70</td><td>0.80</td><td>1.00</td></tr>
  <tr><td>1.25</td><td>1.50</td><td>1.75</td><td>2.00</td><td>2.50</td><td>3.00</td><td>3.50</td><td>4.00</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>13.3 Imperial (UTS) threads — TPI — 21 values</h3>
<table>
  <tr><td>8</td><td>9</td><td>9.5</td><td>10</td><td>11</td><td>12</td><td>14</td></tr>
  <tr><td>16</td><td>18</td><td>19</td><td>20</td><td>22</td><td>24</td><td>28</td></tr>
  <tr><td>32</td><td>36</td><td>38</td><td>40</td><td>44</td><td>48</td><td>56</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>13.4 Default settings (first power-up)</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Setting</th><th>Default</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Motor direction</td><td>CW</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Lead screw pitch</td><td>3 mm</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Dark mode</td><td>On</td></tr>
</table>

<!-- ============================================================= -->
<h2>14. Troubleshooting</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Likely cause / remedy</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Carriage moves the wrong way</td><td>Reverse the <b>Direction</b> setting (Section&nbsp;11.1).</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Feed/thread pitch is wrong by a constant factor</td><td>Check the <b>Lead Screw Pitch</b> value (Section&nbsp;11.2) matches your machine's lead screw.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>RPM reads 0 while spindle turns</td><td>Encoder wiring / coupling problem; confirm the encoder turns with the spindle.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Motor does not move in Feed/Thread mode</td><td>Make sure you confirmed the selection with <b>OK</b>/SELECT (the mode must be <i>engaged</i>, not just selected); verify motor driver power and PUL/DIR wiring.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Touch is offset or unresponsive</td><td>The touchscreen needs panel-specific calibration; have it recalibrated in firmware.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Settings reset after power cycle</td><td>You must press <b>OK</b>/SELECT to <i>save</i> a setting; leaving with Back discards Direction/Pitch changes.</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Carriage keeps moving after you want to stop</td><td>Press <b>BACK</b> from Feed/Thread mode — this disables the motor. Stopping the spindle also stops motion.</td></tr>
</table>

<hr>
